### Quick Sort
- **Time Complexity**: Average case - O(n log n), Worst case - O(n^2), Best case - O(n log n) with good pivot selection.
- **Space Complexity**: O(log n) due to the recursive stack.
```cpp
int partition(int arr[], int low, int high) {
    int pivot = arr[high]; 
    int i = (low - 1);
    for (int j = low; j <= high - 1; j++) {
        if (arr[j] < pivot) {
            i++;
            std::swap(arr[i], arr[j]);
        }
    }
    std::swap(arr[i + 1], arr[high]);
    return (i + 1);
}
void quickSort(int arr[], int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pi = partition(arr, low, high);
        quickSort(arr, low, pi - 1);
        quickSort(arr, pi + 1, high);
    }
}
```

### Heap Sort
- **Time Complexity**: Always O(n log n).
- **Space Complexity**: O(1), in-place.
```cpp
void heapify(int arr[], int n, int i) {
    int largest = i; 
    int left = 2*i + 1; 
    int right = 2*i + 2;
    if (left < n && arr[left] > arr[largest]) largest = left;
    if (right < n && arr[right] > arr[largest]) largest = right;
    if (largest != i) {
        std::swap(arr[i], arr[largest]);
        heapify(arr, n, largest);
    }
}
void heapSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = n / 2 - 1; i >= 0; i--) heapify(arr, n, i);
    for (int i = n-1; i > 0; i--) {
        std::swap(arr[0], arr[i]);
        heapify(arr, i, 0);
    }
}
```

### Comparison and Analysis
- **Bubble, Insertion and Selection Sort** are simpler but less efficient, with bubble sort and insertion sort having a slight advantage when dealing with nearly sorted data.
- **Merge Sort** is highly efficient with stable performance, but it requires additional memory for the temporary arrays.
- **Quick Sort** is often faster in practice, though it can degrade to O(n^2) if not implemented with careful pivot selection.
- **Heap Sort** guarantees O(n log n) performance like merge sort but operates in-place, hence is more memory efficient. However, it can be slower due to in-cache performance and isn't stable.

The space complexity of most sorting algorithms is minimal (O(1)) except for merge sort, which requires extra space for merging. Time complexity varies widely, with some algorithms performing better in specific conditions or dataset distributions.
